{
  "text": "Good morning everyone. Today our group is presenting about Special Olympics BC.\n\nSpecial Olympics BC is part of the larger Special Olympics movement. This movement began because people started to challenge unfair beliefs about people with intellectual disabilities.\n\nIn the early 1960s, Dr. Frank Hayden, a Canadian sport scientist at the University of Toronto, studied students at Beverley School in Toronto. At that time, many people believed children with intellectual disabilities could not be successful in physical activity or sports.\n\nDr. Hayden’s research showed something very important. He found that low fitness was not mainly caused by disability itself. It was caused by a lack of chances to play, train, and participate.\n\nHis research influenced Eunice Kennedy Shriver, who helped organize the first Special Olympics event in Chicago in 1968. Canada was represented there by students from Beverley School. Later, Harry “Red” Foster helped bring Special Olympics to Canada, and the first Canadian Special Olympics event was held in Toronto in 1969.\n\nSpecial Olympics BC began in 1980 with two weekends of games and about 500 participants. Since then, it has grown into year-round programs across British Columbia.\n",
